[[File:St. Johns Anglican Cathedral (5916096950).jpg|thumb|St John's Cathedral, Antigua]] The [[Anglican]] [[diocese]] of '''North East Caribbean and Aruba''' was formed in 1842 as the '''Diocese of Antigua and the Leeward Islands''' when the [[Anglican diocese of Barbados]], then with the [[Diocese of Jamaica]] one of the two dioceses covering the Caribbean, was sub-divided. It celebrated its 175th birthday in 2017.<ref>[http://www.anglican.ink/article/caribbean-diocese-mark-175th-anniversary Anglican (ink)]</ref>
It is now one of the 8 dioceses within the [[Church in the Province of the West Indies|Province of the West Indies]] and comprises the 12 islands of [[Antigua]], [[Barbuda]], [[Dominica]], [[Montserrat]], [[Anguilla]], [[Aruba]], [[Nevis]], [[Saba]], [[Saint Barthélemy|St. Barts]], [[St. Eustatius]], [[St. Kitts]], and [[Saint Martin|St. Martin/St. Maarten]]. The diocesan cathedral is [[St. John's Cathedral (Antigua and Barbuda)|St John's Cathedral]] in St John's Antigua.<ref>[http://www.anglicancommunion.org/structures/member-churches/member-church/diocese.aspx?church=west-indies&dio=north-eastern-caribbean-aruba Anglican Communion]</ref>
There is also a Catholic diocese covering a similar area, the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Saint John's – Basseterre]]
The diocese was under the jurisdiction of the Archbishop of Canterbury from its creation in 1842 until 1883, when the Province of the West Indies was created. Initially the Established Church of the area, and thus supported by public funds, it was disestablished in 1969.
==List of bishops== *(1) 1842–1857 [[Daniel Davis (bishop)|Daniel Davis]] (d. 1857) *(2) 1858–1859 [[Stephen Rigaud]] (1816–1859) *(3) 1860–1895 [[William Walrond Jackson]] (1811–1895) *(4) 1895–1897 [[Charles James Branch]] *(5) 1897–1905 [[Herbert Mather]] *(6) 1905–1910 [[Walter Farrar]] *(7) 1911–1936 [[Edward Hutson]] (also [[Archbishop of the West Indies]], 1922–36) *(8) 1937–1943 [[George Sumner Hand|George Hand]] *(9) 1944–1952 [[Nathaniel Newnham Davis]] *(10) 1953–1969 [[Donald Knowles]] *(11) 1970–1996 [[Orland Lindsay]] *(12) 1996-present [[Errol Brooks]]
