{{Infobox organization |name = |logo = [[File:Saola Working Group Logo.jpg|centre|200px]] ||type = [[Non-profit Organization]] |founded_date = 2006 |founder = |location = |location_country = [[Laos]] and [[Vietnam]] |area_served = [[Annamite Range]] |origins = | key_people = William Robichaud (Coordinator) |focus = [[Saola]] Conservation |method = |revenue = |num_volunteers = 18 |owner = |Non-profit_slogan = |homepage = {{URL|http://www.savethesaola.org/}} |dissolved = |footnotes = }}
The '''Saola Working Group''' '''SWG''' is a working group of the [[IUCN]] Species Survival Commission's Asian Wild Cattle Specialist Group, created in 2006<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.iucn.org/about/union/secretariat/offices/asia/asia_where_work/lao/news_and_events/?7580/Priorities-for-Success--2nd-Meeting-of-the-Saola-Working-Group-wraps-up-in-Vietnam |title = Priorities for Success: 2nd Meeting of the Saola Working Group wraps up in Vietnam |publisher = [[IUCN]] }}</ref> to protect the [[saola]]s (''Pseudoryx nghetinhensis'') and their [[habitat]]. The Conservancy works to engage and incorporate local communities in protecting saolas in [[Annamite Range]] mountains on the border of [[Laos]] and [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.globalwildlife.org/affiliates |title = Affiliates |publisher = Global Wildlife Conservation }}</ref> The Saola is one of the most endangered species in the world. Discovered in 1992 it was the first large mammal new to science in more than 50 years and has never been seen by a biologist in the wild.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/mammals/saola/?204726 |title = Saola still a mystery 20 years after its spectacular debut |publisher = [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] }}</ref> The Saola Working Group is a coalition that includes about 40 experts from the forestry departments of Laos and Vietnam, Vietnam's Institute of Ecology and Biological Resources, Vinh University, biologists and conservationists from [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] and the [[World Wildlife Fund]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/extinction-countdown/2009/09/02/experts-on-the-saola-the-last-chance-to-save-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-mammals/ |title = Experts on the saola: The "Last chance" to save one of the world’s rarest mammals |publisher = [[Scientific American]] }}</ref>
==Programs== The Saola Working Group works with local Laotian communities to educate the importance of the Saola. Villagers are hired to remove hunting snares that are among the biggest threats to the animal. Camera traps to document range and population of Saola are another primary focus.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.mongabay.com/2011/0404-hance_robichaud.html |title = The saola: rushing to save the most 'spectacular zoological discovery' of the 20th Century |publisher = [[Mongabay.com]] }}</ref> New research published showing that leeches can store DNA from their meals for several months has led the SWG to sample leeches in the Annamite Range in hopes to find saola DNA.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.nature.com/news/a-bloody-boon-for-conservation-1.10499 |title = A bloody boon for conservation |publisher = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] }}</ref>
William Robichaud representing the Saola Working Group is a regular featured guest speaker at the annual [[Wildlife Conservation Network]] Expo.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.wildnet.org/events/Saturday_Expo.pdf |title = Wildlife Conservation network Expo 2012 |publisher = [[Wildlife Conservation Network]] }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
