{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen | image = | image_size = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1942}} | birth_place = [[Dresden]], Germany | residence = Germany, Australia, United Kingdom | citizenship = German, Australian, British | nationality = German | fields = [[Environmental Policy]], [[Geography]] | work_institution = [[University of Sussex]], [[University of Hull]] | alma_mater = [[Adelaide University]], [[University of Sussex]] | thesis_title = Limits to the international control of marine pollution | thesis_url = http://www.worldcat.org/title/limits-to-the-international-control-of-marine-pollution/oclc/53601092 | thesis_year = 1981 | doctoral_advisor = | influences = | awards = }}
'''Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen''' (born in 1942) is an [[Emeritus]] [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in the Department of [[Geography]] at the [[University of Hull]] in [[Kingston upon Hull]] England, where she taught environmental policy, management and politics.<ref name=hull>{{cite web | url=http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/geography/about_us/staff.aspx | title=Geography Department: Academic Staff | publisher=[[University of Hull]] | accessdate=29 June 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301012402/http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/geography/about_us/staff.aspx | archivedate=1 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=hullarchive>{{cite web | url=http://www.hull.ac.uk/geog/html/boehmer.html | title=Dr Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen | publisher=[[University of Hull]] | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031206122802/http://www.hull.ac.uk/geog/html/boehmer.html | archivedate=6 December 2003 | accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=spiked>{{cite web | url=http://www.spiked-online.com/index.php?/surveys/2024_article/1308/ | title=Enlightening the Future 2024 Survey – Dr Sonja A Boehmer-Christiansen | publisher=[[Spiked (magazine)|Spiked]] | accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gaia-technology.com/sa/about/forum-member.cfm?ID=3 | title=Scientific Advisory Forum | publisher=The Scientific Alliance | accessdate=29 June 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312211736/http://www.gaia-technology.com/sa/about/forum-member.cfm?ID=3 | archivedate=12 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> She has been editor of the journal ''[[Energy & Environment]]'' since 1998.<ref name=ogel>{{cite web | url=http://www.ogel.org/about-author-a-z-profile.asp?key=635 | title=Dr. Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen | publisher=OGEL | accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen was born in [[Dresden]], [[East Germany]].<ref name=hullarchive/><ref name=ogel/> In 1956, she moved to [[Adelaide]], South Australia, where she obtained a BA with Honours in [[Geomorphology]] from [[Adelaide University]] while also studying climatology, geology, physical geography and German literature.<ref name=ogel/><ref name=bc1982>{{cite journal | last = Boehmer-Christiansen | first = Sonja | title = The scientific basis of marine pollution control | journal = [[Marine Policy]] | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 2–10 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/0308-597X(82)90038-0 | date = January 1982 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0308-597X(82)90038-0 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref><ref name=cru26>{{cite web | last=Boehmer-Christiansen|first= Sonja | date=February 2010 | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmsctech/memo/climatedata/uc2602.htm | title=Memorandum submitted by Dr Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen (CRU 26) | publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] | accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=hoc>{{cite web | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmsctech/387/387ii.pdf | title=The disclosure of climate data from the Climatic Research Unit at the University of East Anglia | volume=II | page=124 | date=24 March 2010 | publisher=[[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] | accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> She moved again to England in 1969 and later attended the [[University of Sussex]] where she first obtained an MA followed by a DPhil in International Relations in 1981.<ref name=hullarchive/><ref name=bc1982/><ref>{{cite journal | last=Boehmer-Christiansen|first= Sonja A. | url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/74117811717l3360/ | title=Emerging international principles of environmental protection and their impact on Britain | journal=The Environmentalist | volume=10 | issue=2 | year=1990 | page=95 | doi=10.1007/bf02244387}}</ref> Her doctoral thesis was titled, ''Limits to the international control of marine pollution''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Boehmer-Christiansen|first= S.A. | url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/limits-to-the-international-control-of-marine-pollution/oclc/53601092 | title=Limits to the international control of marine pollution | year=1981 | publisher=University of Sussex | accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref>
==Career== Boehmer-Christiansen joined the [[Science and Technology Policy Research|Science and Technology Policy Research Unit (SPRU)]] at the University of Sussex in 1985, working for a decade as a Research Fellow and then later as a Visiting Fellow.<ref name=hullarchive/><ref name=cru26/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Units/spru/publications/annualreport/1998/docs/38-39.pdf | title=SPRU Annual Report – SPRU Staff: Associate Staff – Visiting Fellows and Professors | year=1998 | page=39 | publisher=[[University of Sussex]] | accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref> Since the mid-1990s she had taught environmental policy, management and politics in the Geography Department at the University of Hull.<ref name=spiked/><ref name=hoc/> As an Emeritus Reader she still works from the University of Hull's Geography Department.<ref name=hull/><ref name=cru26/>
She is a past member of the [[United Nations Environment Programme|United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)]] [[Stakeholder Forum for a Sustainable Future]].<ref name=hullarchive/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stakeholderforum.org/sf/mediafiles/sf_annual_report_02.pdf | title=Stakeholder Forum – Annual Report 2001–2002 | year=2002 | page=25 | publisher=[[Stakeholder Forum for a Sustainable Future|Stakeholder Forum]] | accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref>
==Views on Climate change== When asked about the publication in the Spring of 2003 of a revised version of the paper at the center of the [[Soon and Baliunas controversy]], Boehmer-Christiansen said, "I'm following my political agenda -- a bit, anyway. But isn't that the right of the editor?"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Monastersky|first=Richard|title=Storm Brews Over Global Warming|journal=[[Chronicle of Higher Education]]|date=5 September 2003|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Storm-Brews-Over-Global/27779/}}</ref>
Boehmer-Christiansen has been a critic of [[global climate models|climate models]] saying they are based on data that cannot be verified.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/08/24/1093246516150.html | title=Tuvalu's tides divide scientists | publisher=[[The Age]] | date=25 August 2004 | accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref> In 2006, she signed an open letter to Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] urging him to open the [[Kyoto Protocol]] to debate by holding balanced, comprehensive public-consultation sessions on the Canadian government's climate change plans.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/financialpost/story.html?id=3711460e-bd5a-475d-a6be-4db87559d605 | title=Open Kyoto to debate – An open letter to Prime Minister Stephen Harper | publisher=[[National Post]] | date=11 April 2006 | accessdate=1 July 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512140810/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/financialpost/story.html?id=3711460e-bd5a-475d-a6be-4db87559d605 | archivedate=12 May 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>
She describes herself as agnostic on whether humans are causing [[global warming]], and believes its negative aspects to be politically exaggerated.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fcpp.org/publication.php/3348 | title=Conversations From the Frotier with Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen, Geomorphologist | publisher=Frontier Centre for Public Policy | date=29 June 2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726050446/http://www.fcpp.org/publication.php/3348|archivedate=26 July 2011}}</ref>
==Third-party views== According to [[Fred Pearce]], Boehmer-Christiansen is a [[Environmental skepticism|sceptic]] about [[acid rain]] and [[global warming]] and calls the science reports produced by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] "political constructs."<ref name="Pearce">[[Fred Pearce|Pearce, Fred]], ''The Climate Files: The Battle for the Truth about Global Warming'', (2010) [[Guardian Books]], {{ISBN|978-0-85265-229-9}}, p. XIV.</ref>
''The Guardian'' reported that Boehmer-Christiansen published – against the recommendations of a [[peer review|reviewer]] – a paper in ''[[Energy & Environment]]'' claiming that the Sun is made of iron.<ref name=guardian2011>{{cite news | last=Barley|first= Shanta | url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/feb/25/real-climate-libel-threat | title=Real Climate faces libel suit| publisher=[[The Guardian]] | date=25 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Manuel | first=Oliver K. | url=http://multi-science.metapress.com/content/v3600623g8txh577/ | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130128141051/http://multi-science.metapress.com/content/v3600623g8txh577/ | dead-url=yes | archive-date=2013-01-28 | title=Earth's Heat Source – The Sun | journal=[[Energy & Environment]] | volume=20 | issue=1–2 | pages=131–144 | year=2009 | doi=10.1260/095830509787689178 | arxiv=0905.0704 }}</ref>
